    An "International Conference on Cycles in Graphs" took place at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tennessee, from Wednesday, May 30, 2012 until Saturday, June 2, 2012.  This was held in conjunction with the 27th Annual Shanks Lectures at Vanderbilt University.  The conference location was the Stevenson Center of Vanderbilt University. The local organizers were Mark Ellingham (the principal investigator) and Paul Edelman.

    The conference focused on the area of cycles in graphs.  This is a fundamental area of research in graph theory, but there has not been a meeting specifically dedicated to this topic for the past ten years, or perhaps longer.  The conference featured eight plenary talks by seven distinguished speakers, as follows:

 *  Daniela K&uuml;hn (University of Birmingham, U.K.) was the Shanks Lecturer, and gave two talks;
 *  Alan Frieze (Carnegie Mellon University);
 *  Penny Haxell (University of Waterloo, Canada);
 *  Deryk Osthus (University of Birmingham, U.K.);
 *  Kenta Ozeki (National Institute of Informatics, Japan);
 *  Paul Seymour (Princeton University); and
 *  Xingxing Yu (Georgia Institute of Technology).

    There were also 68 twenty-minute talks (with five additional minutes for questions) by other speakers.  These talks ran in two parallel sessions throughout the conference.  The talks covered many different topics on cycles in graphs and closely related areas.  The conference seems to have been a definite success and to have achieved its goal of allowing participants to see some of the most important new developments in the area.

    Most of the National Science Foundation (NSF) funding was used to provide travel support to participants who requested support via an application process.  22 people were supported in this way, including 8 graduate students and 6 postdoctoral fellows.  NSF funding also paid for some of the expenses of the plenary speakers, and a small amount was used to pay parking expenses for participants in general.

    The conference web site may be found at
        http://www.math.vanderbilt.edu/~shanks2012/
The "Program" link provides an outline of the program, with clickable links to abstracts of talks.  The "Slides for Talks" link leads to a page where files containing slides for some of the talks (submitted by participants on a voluntary basis) may be found.

